In .NET 8+ (including .NET 10), the framework already ships the abstraction you need: **`System.TimeProvider`**.

**Usage in your production code:**

```csharp
public class ReportGenerator
{
    private readonly TimeProvider _timeProvider;

    public ReportGenerator(TimeProvider timeProvider)
    {
        _timeProvider = timeProvider;
    }

    public Report Generate()
    {
        var now = _timeProvider.GetUtcNow(); // instead of DateTime.UtcNow
        // ...
    }
}
```

**In production (DI registration):**

```csharp
services.AddSingleton(TimeProvider.System);
```

**In tests (deterministic):**

```csharp
using Microsoft.Extensions.Time.Testing; // from Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing NuGet

var fakeTime = new FakeTimeProvider(new DateTimeOffset(2026, 1, 15, 9, 0, 0, TimeSpan.Zero));
var generator = new ReportGenerator(fakeTime);

var report = generator.Generate();
// assertions against the fixed timestamp

fakeTime.Advance(TimeSpan.FromHours(1)); // simulate time passing
```

**Package to install for tests:**

```
dotnet add package Microsoft.Extensions.TimeProvider.Testing
```

No need to create a custom interface — `TimeProvider` is the built-in abstraction and `FakeTimeProvider` is the official test double.
